-- ─── DIASTASIS RECTI REHABILITATION ──────────────────────────────────────────
('Diastasis Recti – Tension Test and Assessment',
 'core', array[], array['core'],
 'rehab', 'other', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Diastasis recti (DR) is the separation of the rectus abdominis muscles along the linea alba. Self-check: lie on your back, knees bent. Place fingers horizontally on the midline (navel). Lift just the head and shoulders. Feel for a gap: less than 2 finger-widths wide with tension (the tissue feels firm when you press) = functional. More than 2 fingers wide or no tension felt = consult a pelvic floor physiotherapist. Important: the GAP is less important than the TENSION in the linea alba. Many exercises are appropriate even with a larger gap if tension is present. Avoid: traditional crunches, sit-ups, heavy lifting, planks, and exercises that cause doming or coning of the belly.',
 'Doing standard crunches or sit-ups with diastasis recti; ignoring the issue and pushing through traditional core training; over-restricting all exercise unnecessarily when tension is adequate; not seeking physiotherapy assessment.',
 'diastasis_recti', array['Gap vs tension: the gap is less important than the tension — assess both','Doming = stop: if the midline domes or cones during any exercise, that exercise is contraindicated','Physio referral: any uncertainty warrants a pelvic floor physiotherapy assessment','Appropriate exercise continues: DR does not mean no exercise — it means MODIFIED exercise'],
 array['Full pelvic floor physiotherapy assessment','DR rehabilitation program with physiotherapist','Return to running and high-impact assessment'],
 array['Basic postnatal breathing only','Gentle stretching','Rest and awareness phase'],
 array['postnatal','diastasis_recti','assessment','linea_alba','core_separation','rehabilitation'], array[],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 60, null, true),

('Diastasis Recti – Dead Bug Modification',
 'core', array['hip_flexors'], array['core'],
 'rehab', 'other', array['bodyweight'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Modified dead bug for DR: lie on the back, knees bent to 90°, arms to the ceiling. Inhale to prepare. On the exhale, gently draw in the abdomen (without doming), maintain the brace, and extend ONE leg to 45° as the SAME-side arm extends overhead. Inhale to return. Alternate sides. CHECK: does the midline dome or cone during the movement? If yes — too demanding, regress. This exercise trains the anti-rotation and anti-extension function of the deep core while maintaining appropriate tension on the linea alba. Only progress when there is no doming and good tension is maintained.',
 'Any doming or coning of the midline (immediately regress the exercise — this is the primary monitoring cue for DR); breath holding; full leg extension before mastering the 45° range; not monitoring the midline throughout.',
 'diastasis_recti', array['Watch the midline: any doming = regress immediately','Same-side arm and leg: contralateral is harder — save for later','45° first: full range later only if midline stays flat','Exhale on the movement: core braces with the exhalation'],
 array['Contralateral arm-leg extension','Dead bug with full range extension','Dead bug with resistance band around the feet'],
 array['Heel slide (earlier stage)','Breathing and pelvic floor activation','Supine glute bridge (posterior chain, less core demand)'],
 array['postnatal','diastasis_recti','dead_bug','modified','linea_alba','core_stability'], array['diastasis_recti_severe_no_tension'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 3, 8, null, 60, true),

('Diastasis Recti – Standing Core Progressions',
 'core', array['glutes','shoulder'], array['core','glutes'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['resistance_band'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Standing exercises are more functional and appropriate for DR than floor exercises in many cases. Gravity assists in managing intra-abdominal pressure. Standing progressions: (1) Standing resistance band pull-apart (scapular retraction + core brace); (2) Standing pallof press (anti-rotation core stability); (3) Standing single-arm cable or band press (anti-extension and rotation); (4) Single-leg standing with contralateral arm reach (balance and core challenge). For all: brace gently, breathe through, and monitor for any midline doming.',
 'Performing these exercises without mastering the breath-brace coordination first; using too much resistance (midline will dome under excess load); progressing too quickly from floor to standing before adequate tension is restored in the linea alba.',
 'diastasis_recti', array['Standing is often easier: gravity helps manage pressure','Pallof press is excellent: anti-rotation core is functional','Monitor midline: even standing — watch for doming','Progress from horizontal: earn each position through the progressions'],
 array['Loaded carries (suitcase carry for lateral stability)','Return to resistance training full body','Return to high-impact activities (assessed by physiotherapist)'],
 array['Dead bug modification on the floor','Supine glute bridge','Heel slide core reconnection'],
 array['postnatal','diastasis_recti','standing','functional','pallof_press','anti_rotation'], array['diastasis_recti_severe_no_tension'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 3, 12, null, 60, true),

-- ─── POSTNATAL RETURN TO TRAINING (6–12 WEEKS+) ──────────────────────────────
('Postnatal Return to Training – Walk to Run Program',
 'cardiovascular', array['quadriceps','glutes'], array['cardiovascular','quadriceps'],
 'running', 'other', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Minimum 12 weeks postnatally before return to running (BJSM 2019 guidelines). Prerequisites: able to walk briskly for 30 minutes without pain; single-leg calf raise 20 reps each side; single-leg squat 10 reps each side; no pelvic floor symptoms (leaking, prolapse heaviness). Walk-to-run program: Week 1-2: 1-minute run / 1-minute walk × 10 intervals. Week 3-4: 2-minute run / 1-minute walk × 8. Week 5-6: 3-minute run / 1-minute walk × 6. Progress only when symptom-free. Stop if any leaking, prolapse symptoms, or pain occur.',
 'Returning to running before 12 weeks postnatally (high risk of pelvic floor injury); not assessing the prerequisites before beginning (single-leg strength, pelvic floor symptoms); ignoring symptoms during the run (any leaking or prolapse heaviness is a red flag to stop and reassess).',
 'postnatal', array['12 weeks minimum: this is evidence-based — not arbitrary','Test prerequisites first: single-leg strength and no pelvic floor symptoms','Walk-run intervals: gradual re-introduction of impact','Listen to your body: symptoms are stop signs — not inconveniences'],
 array['Return to 5K running','Return to interval running training','Return to team sports (requires additional assessment)'],
 array['Walking only (earlier stage)','Pool running with belt (no impact)','Cycling (low impact cardio)'],
 array['postnatal','return_to_running','walk_run','12_weeks','pelvic_floor','impact_grading'], array['pelvic_organ_prolapse_symptomatic','stress_incontinence_active'],
 'locomotion', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 1800, null, true),

('Postnatal Strength Return – Bodyweight Squat Progression',
 'quadriceps', array['glutes','hamstrings','core'], array['quadriceps','glutes'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', true,
 'Progressive return to squatting strength after childbirth. Phase 1 (weeks 6-8): Sit-to-stand from chair, 3×15. Phase 2 (weeks 8-12): Bodyweight squat with perfect mechanics, 3×20. Phase 3 (weeks 12+): Goblet squat with light weight, 3×15. Phase 4 (weeks 16+): Barbell back squat or front squat at reduced weight from pre-pregnancy, 3×10. Coordinate pelvic floor lift with exhalation on the ascent. Monitor: no leaking, no prolapse heaviness, no pelvic or hip pain. Progress only when symptom-free.',
 'Rushing phases (skipping from chair squat to barbell squat in 8 weeks — too fast); not monitoring pelvic floor symptoms during the squat (any leaking means regression is needed); using pre-pregnancy weights too early; ignoring doming of the midline during loaded squats.',
 'postnatal', array['Exhale up: coordinate pelvic floor lift with the ascent','Symptom monitoring: leaking or heaviness = regress immediately','Phases take weeks: do not rush — the phases are minimum timeframes','Start light: pre-pregnancy strength returns but takes months — be patient'],
 array['Loaded barbell squat return to pre-pregnancy levels','Bulgarian split squat for unilateral strength','Squat-based high-intensity training programs'],
 array['Sit-to-stand from chair only (earliest stage)','Supported squat with TRX','Wall squat isometric'],
 array['postnatal','return_to_training','squat','progressive','pelvic_floor','strength_return'], array['pelvic_organ_prolapse_symptomatic'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 3, 15, null, 60, true),

('Postnatal Feeding Posture & Upper Body Recovery',
 'back', array['shoulder','core'], array['back','shoulder'],
 'rehab', 'other', array['bodyweight','resistance_band'], 'beginner', false,
 'Breastfeeding and bottle-feeding create repetitive forward flexion posture: head forward, shoulders rounded, thoracic kyphosis increased. Counter-exercises: (1) Thoracic extension over a foam roller (place the roller perpendicular to the spine at the mid-back, arms crossed, allow the head to drop back in gentle extension) — 3×60 seconds each vertebral level. (2) Chin tuck × 20. (3) Band pull-apart × 20 for scapular retraction. (4) Doorway chest stretch hold 30 seconds × 3. This counters feeding posture and reduces the epidemic of postnatal neck and upper back pain.',
 'Using the foam roller at the lower back (not appropriate for most — use only in the thoracic region from T4-T10); rolling too aggressively; neglecting this corrective work entirely despite hours of feeding posture daily.',
 'postnatal', array['Feeding is the enemy of posture: counter it deliberately','Foam roller placement: mid-back only (T4-T10), not lower back','Daily practice: 5-10 minutes after each main feeding session','Chin tuck first: decompresses the cervical spine before extending'],
 array['Regular upper body posture correction program','Rowing exercises with resistance band or cable','Thoracic mobilisation yoga class'],
 array['Gentle chin tuck only (earliest stage)','Thoracic extension stretch against a wall','Sitting posture correction during feeding only'],
 array['postnatal','feeding_posture','upper_back','thoracic','corrective','neck_pain'], array['cervical_instability'],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', false, 3, null, 60, 30, true);

